# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: christmas-in-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] This is a complete **list of acts of the 1st session of the 5th Parliament of the United Kingdom** which had regnal year **1 Geo.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] This session met from 17 March 1715 until 26 June 1716.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] For acts passed until 1707, see the list of acts of the Parliament of England and the list of acts of the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] See also the list of acts of the Parliament of Ireland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] For acts passed from 1801 onwards, see the list of acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] For acts of the devolved parliaments and assemblies in the United Kingdom, see the list of acts of the Scottish Parliament, the list of acts of the Northern Ireland Assembly, and the list of acts and measures of Senedd Cymru; see also the list of acts of the Parliament of Northern Ireland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] The number shown after each act's title is its chapter number.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Acts are cited using this number, preceded by the year(s) of the reign during which the relevant parliamentary session was held; thus the Union with Ireland Act 1800 is cited as "39 & 40 Geo.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] 67", meaning the 67th act passed during the session that started in the 39th year of the reign of George III and which finished in the 40th year of that reign.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Note that the modern convention is to use Arabic numerals in citations (thus "41 Geo.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Acts of the last session of the Parliament of Great Britain and the first session of the Parliament of the United Kingdom are both cited as "41 Geo.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Acts passed by the Parliament of Great Britain did not have a short title; however, some of these acts have subsequently been given a short title by acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom (such as the Short Titles Act 1896).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Before the Acts of Parliament (Commencement) Act 1793 came into force on 8 April 1793, acts passed by the Parliament of Great Britain were deemed to have come into effect on the first day of the session in which they were passed.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Because of this, the years given in the list below may in fact be the year before a particular act was passed.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] The first session of the 5th Parliament of Great Britain, which met from 17 March 1715 until 26 June 1716.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] This session was also traditionally cited as **1 Geo.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Woollen Manufacture Act 1711 (10 Ann. c.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Embezzlement of Public Stores Act 1697 (9 Will.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/1-geo-1-st-2] Foreign Protestants Naturalization Act 1708 (7 Ann. c.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/10-ann] This is a complete **list of acts of the Parliament of Great Britain for the year 1711**.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/10-ann] The second session of the 3rd Parliament of Great Britain, which met from 7 December 1711 until 21 June 1712.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/10-ann] This is the citation in *The Statutes at Large*.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/10-ann] Kilburn Bridge was located where the Edgware Road (Kilburn High Road) crossed the River Westbourne.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/10-ann] Sparrows Herne was a settlement located between Bushey and Bushey Heath.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/10-ann] The section of the A411 road in the area continues the name.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/10-ann] New Churches in London and Westminster Act 1710 (9 Ann. c.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/10-ann] Minehead Harbour Act 1700 (12 & 13 Will.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens wrote *A Christmas Carol* during a period when the British were exploring and re-evaluating past Christmas traditions, including carols, and newer customs such as cards and Christmas trees.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He was influenced by the experiences of his own youth and by the Christmas stories of other authors, including Washington Irving and Douglas Jerrold.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens had written three Christmas stories prior to the novella, and was inspired following a visit to the Field Lane Ragged School, one of several establishments for London's street children.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The treatment of the poor and the ability of a selfish man to redeem himself by transforming into a more sympathetic character are the key themes of the story.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] There is discussion among academics as to whether this is a fully secular story or a Christian allegory.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Published on 19 December, the first edition sold out by Christmas Eve; by the end of 1844 thirteen editions had been released.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Most critics reviewed the novella favourably.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The story was illicitly copied in January 1844; Dickens took legal action against the publishers, who went bankrupt, further reducing Dickens's small profits from the publication.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He subsequently wrote four other Christmas stories.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In 1849 he began public readings of the story, which proved so successful he undertook 127 further performances until 1870, the year of his death.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] *A Christmas Carol* has never been out of print and has been translated into several languages; the story has been adapted many times for film, stage, opera and other media.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] That night Scrooge is visited at home by Marley's ghost, who wanders the Earth entwined by heavy chains and money boxes forged during a lifetime of greed and selfishness.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Marley tells Scrooge that he has a single chance to avoid the same fate: he will be visited by three spirits and must listen or be cursed to carry much heavier chains of his own.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The first spirit, the Ghost of Christmas Past, takes Scrooge to Christmas scenes of Scrooge's boyhood, reminding him of a time when he was more innocent.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The scenes reveal Scrooge's lonely childhood at boarding school, his relationship with his beloved sister Fan, the long-dead mother of Fred, and a Christmas party hosted by his first employer, Mr Fezziwig, who treated him like a son.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge's neglected fiancée Belle is shown ending their relationship, as she realises that he will never love her as much as he loves money.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Finally, they visit a now-married Belle with her large, happy family on the Christmas Eve that Marley died.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge, upset by hearing a description of the man that he has become, demands that the ghost remove him from the house.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The second spirit, the Ghost of Christmas Present, takes Scrooge to a joyous market where people are buying the makings of Christmas dinner and to celebrations of Christmas in a miner's cottage and in a lighthouse.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge and the ghost also visit Fred's Christmas party.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] A major part of this stave is taken up with Bob Cratchit's family feast and introduces his youngest son, Tiny Tim, a happy boy who is seriously ill.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The spirit informs Scrooge that Tiny Tim will die unless the course of events changes.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Before disappearing, the spirit shows Scrooge two hideous, emaciated children named Ignorance and Want.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He tells Scrooge to beware the former above all and mocks Scrooge's concern for their welfare.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The third spirit, the Ghost of Christmas Yet to Come, shows Scrooge a Christmas Day in the future.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The silent ghost reveals scenes involving the death of a disliked man whose funeral is attended by local businessmen only on condition that lunch is provided.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] His charwoman, laundress and the local undertaker steal his possessions to sell to a fence.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] When he asks the spirit to show a single person who feels emotion over his death, he is only given the pleasure of a poor couple who rejoice that his death gives them more time to put their finances in order.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] When Scrooge asks to see tenderness connected with any death, the ghost shows him Bob Cratchit and his family mourning the death of Tiny Tim.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The ghost then allows Scrooge to see a neglected grave, with a tombstone bearing Scrooge's name.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Sobbing, Scrooge pledges to change his ways.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge awakens on Christmas morning a changed man.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He makes a large donation to the charity he rejected the previous day, anonymously sends a large turkey to the Cratchit home for Christmas dinner and spends the afternoon at Fred's Christmas party.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The following day he gives Cratchit an increase in pay, and begins to become a father figure to Tiny Tim.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] From then on Scrooge treats everyone with kindness, generosity and compassion, embodying the spirit of Christmas.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The writer Charles Dickens was born to a middle-class family which got into financial difficulties as a result of the spendthrift nature of his father John.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In 1824 John was committed to the Marshalsea, a debtors' prison in Southwark, London.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens, aged 12, was forced to pawn his collection of books, leave school and work at a dirty and rat-infested shoe-blacking factory.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The change in circumstances gave him what his biographer, Michael Slater, describes as a "deep personal and social outrage", which heavily influenced his writing and outlook.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] By the end of 1842 Dickens was a well-established author with six major works as well as several short stories, novellas and other pieces.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] On 31 December that year he began publishing his novel *Martin Chuzzlewit* as a monthly serial; it was his favourite work, but sales were disappointing and he faced temporary financial difficulties.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Celebrating the Christmas season had been growing in popularity through the Victorian era.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The Christmas tree was introduced in Britain during the 18th century, and its use was popularised by Queen Victoria and Prince Albert.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In the early 19th century there had been a revival of interest in Christmas carols, following a decline in popularity over the previous hundred years.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The publication of Davies Gilbert's 1823 work *Some Ancient Christmas Carols, With the Tunes to Which They Were Formerly Sung in the West of England* and William Sandys's 1833 collection *Christmas Carols, Ancient and Modern* led to a growth in the form's popularity in Britain.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens had an interest in Christmas, and his first story on the subject was "Christmas Festivities", published in *Bell's Weekly Messenger* in 1835; the story was then published as "A Christmas Dinner" in *Sketches by Boz* (1836).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] "The Story of the Goblins Who Stole a Sexton", another Christmas story, appeared in the 1836 novel *The Pickwick Papers*.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In the episode, a Mr Wardle describes a misanthropic sexton, Gabriel Grub, who undergoes a Christmas conversion after being visited by goblins who show him the past and future.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Slater considers that "the main elements of the *Carol* are present in the story", but not yet in a firm form.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The story is followed by a passage about Christmas in Dickens's editorial *Master Humphrey's Clock*.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The professor of English literature Paul Davis writes that although the "Goblins" story appears to be a prototype of *A Christmas Carol*, all Dickens's earlier writings about Christmas influenced the story.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens was not the first author to celebrate the Christmas season in literature.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Among earlier authors who influenced Dickens was Washington Irving, whose 1819–20 work *The Sketch Book of Geoffrey Crayon, Gent.* included four essays on old English Christmas traditions that he experienced while staying at Aston Hall near Birmingham.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The tales and essays attracted Dickens, and the two authors shared the belief that returning to Christmas traditions might promote a type of social connection that they felt had been lost in the modern world.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Several works had an influence on the writing of *A Christmas Carol*, including two essays by his friend Douglas Jerrold: one from an 1841 issue of *Punch*, "How Mr.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Chokepear Keeps a Merry Christmas" and one from 1843, "The Beauties of the Police".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] More broadly, Dickens was influenced by fairy tales and nursery stories, which he closely associated with Christmas, because he saw them as stories of conversion and transformation.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens was touched by the lot of poor children in the middle decades of the 19th century.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In early 1843 he toured the Cornish tin mines, where he was angered by seeing children working in appalling conditions.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The suffering he witnessed there was reinforced by a visit to the Field Lane Ragged School, one of several London schools set up for the education of the capital's half-starved, illiterate street children.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In February 1843 the *Second Report of the Children's Employment Commission* was published.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] It was a parliamentary report exposing the effects of the Industrial Revolution upon working class children.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Horrified by what he read, Dickens planned to publish an inexpensive political pamphlet tentatively titled, *An Appeal to the People of England, on behalf of the Poor Man's Child*, but changed his mind, deferring the pamphlet's production until the end of the year.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] By mid-1843 Dickens was suffering from financial problems.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Sales of *Martin Chuzzlewit* were falling off, and his wife, Catherine, was pregnant with their fifth child.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Matters worsened when Chapman & Hall, his publishers, threatened to reduce his monthly income by £50 if sales dropped further.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He began *A Christmas Carol* in October 1843.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Michael Slater, Dickens's biographer, describes the book as being "written at white heat"; it was completed in six weeks, the final pages being written in early December.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He built much of the work in his head while taking night-time walks of 15 to 20 miles (24 to 32 km) around London.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's sister-in-law wrote how he "wept, and laughed, and wept again, and excited himself in a most extraordinary manner, in composition".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] George Cruikshank, the illustrator who had earlier worked with Dickens on *Sketches by Boz* (1836) and *Oliver Twist* (1838), introduced him to the caricaturist John Leech.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] By 24 October Dickens invited Leech to work on *A Christmas Carol*, and four hand-coloured etchings and four black-and-white wood engravings by the artist accompanied the text.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's hand-written manuscript of the story does not include the sentence in the penultimate paragraph "... and to Tiny Tim, who did *not* die"; this was added later, during the printing process.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] This psychological conflict may be responsible for the two radically different Scrooges in the tale—one a cold, stingy and greedy semi-recluse, the other a benevolent, sociable man.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge could also be based on two misers: the eccentric John Elwes, MP, or Jemmy Wood, the owner of the Gloucester Old Bank and also known as "The Gloucester Miser".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Elwell, Scrooge's views on the poor are a reflection of those of the demographer and political economist Thomas Malthus, while the miser's questions "Are there no prisons? ...
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] There are literary precursors for Scrooge in Dickens's own works.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Douglas-Fairhurst sees that the minor character Gabriel Grub from *The Pickwick Papers* was also an influence when creating Scrooge.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] It is possible that Scrooge's name came from a tombstone Dickens had seen on a visit to Edinburgh.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The grave was for Ebenezer Lennox Scroggie, whose job was given as a meal man—a corn merchant; Dickens misread the inscription as "mean man".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] This theory has been described as "a probable Dickens hoax" for which "[n]o one could find any corroborating evidence".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] When Dickens was young he lived near a tradesman's premises with the sign "Goodge and Marney", which may have provided the name for Scrooge's former business partner.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] For the chained Marley, Dickens drew on his memory of a visit to the Western Penitentiary in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, in March 1842, where he saw—and was affected by seeing—fettered prisoners.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] For the character Tiny Tim, Dickens used his nephew Henry, a disabled boy who was five at the time *A Christmas Carol* was written.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The two figures of Want and Ignorance, sheltering in the robes of the Ghost of Christmas Present, were inspired by the children Dickens had seen on his visit to a ragged school in the East End of London.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The transformation of Scrooge is central to the story.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Some writers, including the Dickens scholar Grace Moore, consider that there is a Christian theme running through *A Christmas Carol*, and that the novella should be seen as an allegory of the Christian concept of redemption.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's biographer Claire Tomalin sees the conversion of Scrooge as carrying the Christian message that "even the worst of sinners may repent and become a good man".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's attitudes towards organised religion were complex; he based his beliefs and principles on the New Testament.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] His statement that Marley "had no bowels" is a reference to the "bowels of compassion" mentioned in the First Epistle of John, the reason for his eternal damnation.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Other writers, including Kelly, consider that Dickens put forward a "secular vision of this sacred holiday".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] From a secular viewpoint, the cultural historian Penne Restad suggests that Scrooge's redemption underscores "the conservative, individualistic and patriarchal aspects" of Dickens's "*Carol* philosophy" of charity and altruism.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens wrote *A Christmas Carol* in response to British social attitudes towards poverty, particularly child poverty, and wished to use the novella as a means to put forward his arguments against it.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The story shows Scrooge as a paradigm for self-interest, and the possible repercussions of ignoring the poor, especially children—personified by the allegorical figures of Want and Ignorance.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The two figures were created to arouse sympathy with readers—as was Tiny Tim.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Douglas-Fairhurst observes that the use of such figures allowed Dickens to present his message of the need for charity without alienating his largely middle-class readership.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] As the result of the disagreements with Chapman and Hall over the commercial failures of *Martin Chuzzlewit*, Dickens arranged to pay for the publishing himself, in exchange for a percentage of the profits.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Production of *A Christmas Carol* was not without problems.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The first printing was meant to have festive green endpapers, but they came out a dull olive colour.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's publisher Chapman and Hall replaced these with yellow endpapers and reworked the title page in harmonising red and blue shades.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The final product was bound in red cloth with gilt-edged pages, completed only two days before the publication date of 19 December 1843.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Following publication, Dickens arranged for the manuscript to be bound in red Morocco leather and presented as a gift to his solicitor, Thomas Mitton.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Priced at five shillings (equivalent to £27 in 2025), the first run of 6,000 copies sold out by Christmas Eve.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Chapman and Hall issued second and third editions before the new year, and the book continued to sell well into 1844.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] By the end of 1844 eleven more editions had been released.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Since its initial publication the book has been issued in numerous hardback and paperback editions, translated into several languages and has never been out of print.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] It was Dickens's most popular book in the United States, and sold over two million copies in the hundred years following its first publication there.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The high production costs upon which Dickens insisted led to reduced profits, and the first edition brought him only £230 (equivalent to £25,000 in 2025) rather than the £1,000 (equivalent to £110,000 in 2025) he expected.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] A year later, the profits were only £744, and Dickens was deeply disappointed.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] According to Douglas-Fairhurst, contemporary reviews of *A Christmas Carol* "were almost uniformly kind".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] *The Illustrated London News* described how the story's "impressive eloquence ... its unfeigned lightness of heart—its playful and sparkling humour ... its gentle spirit of humanity" all put the reader "in good humour with ourselves, with each other, with the season and with the author".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] After Dickens's death, Margaret Oliphant deplored the turkey and plum pudding aspects of the book but admitted that in the days of its first publication it was regarded as "a new gospel", and noted that the book was unique in that it made people behave better.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The religious press generally ignored the tale but, in January 1844, *Christian Remembrancer* thought the tale's old and hackneyed subject was treated in an original way and praised the author's sense of humour and pathos.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The writer and social thinker John Ruskin told a friend that he thought Dickens had taken the religion from Christmas, and had imagined it as "mistletoe and pudding—neither resurrection from the dead, nor rising of new stars, nor teaching of wise men, nor shepherds".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] *The New Monthly Magazine* praised the story, but thought the book's physical excesses—the gilt edges and expensive binding—kept the price high, making it unavailable to the poor.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The review recommended that the tale should be printed on cheap paper and priced accordingly.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] An unnamed writer for *The Westminster Review* mocked Dickens's grasp of economics, asking "Who went without turkey and punch in order that Bob Cratchit might get them—for, unless there were turkeys and punch in surplus, someone must go without".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens had criticised the US in *American Notes* and *Martin Chuzzlewit*, making American readers reluctant to embrace his work, but by the end of the American Civil War, the book had gained wide recognition in American households.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In 1863 *The New York Times* published an enthusiastic review, noting that the author brought the "old Christmas ... of bygone centuries and remote manor houses, into the living rooms of the poor of today".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In January 1844 Parley's Illuminated Library published an unauthorised version of the story in a condensed form which they sold for twopence.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Two days after the release of the Parley version, Dickens sued on the basis of copyright infringement and won.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The publishers declared themselves bankrupt and Dickens was left to pay £700 in costs.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The small profits Dickens earned from *A Christmas Carol* further strained his relationship with his publishers, and he broke with them in favour of Bradbury and Evans, who had been printing his works to that point.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens returned to the tale several times during his life to amend the phrasing and punctuation.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] While the public eagerly bought the later books, the reviewers were highly critical of the stories.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] By 1849 Dickens was engaged with *David Copperfield* and had neither the time nor the inclination to produce another Christmas book.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He decided the best way to reach his audience with his "Carol philosophy" was by public readings.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] During Christmas 1853 he gave a reading in Birmingham Town Hall to the Industrial and Literary Institute.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He insisted that tickets be reserved for working-class attendees at quarter-price and the performance was a great success.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Initially he donated the profits to good causes, although from 1858 he read the book for profit.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] He read the tale in an abbreviated version 127 times, until 1870 (the year of his death), including at his farewell performance.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In the years following the book's publication, responses to the tale were published by W.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Swepstone (*Christmas Shadows*, 1850), Horatio Alger (*Job Warner's Christmas*, 1863), Louisa May Alcott (*A Christmas Dream, and How It Came True*, 1882), and others who followed Scrooge's life as a reformed man – or some who thought Dickens had got it wrong and needed to be corrected.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The novella was adapted for the stage almost immediately.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Three productions opened on 5 February 1844, one by Edward Stirling, *A Christmas Carol; or, Past, Present, and Future*, being sanctioned by Dickens and running for more than 40 nights.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] By the close of February 1844 eight rival *A Christmas Carol* theatrical productions were playing in London.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The story has been adapted for film and television more than any of Dickens's other works.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In 1901 it was produced as *Scrooge, or, Marley's Ghost*, a silent black-and-white British film; it was one of the first known adaptations of a Dickens work on film, but it is now largely lost.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The story was adapted in 1923 for BBC radio.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] It has been adapted to other media, including opera, ballet, animation, stage musicals and a BBC mime production starring Marcel Marceau.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Davis considers the adaptations have become better remembered than the original.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Some of Dickens's scenes—such as visiting the miners and lighthouse keepers—have been forgotten by many, while other events often added—such as Scrooge visiting the Cratchits on Christmas Day—are now thought by many to be part of the original story.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Accordingly, Davis distinguishes between the original text and the "remembered version".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The phrase "Merry Christmas" had been around for many years—the earliest known written use was in a letter in 1534—but Dickens's use of the phrase in *A Christmas Carol* popularised it among the Victorian public.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Humbug!" entered popular use in the English language as a retort to anything sentimental or overly festive; the name "Scrooge" became used as a designation for a miser and was added to the *Oxford English Dictionary* as such in 1982.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In the early 19th century the celebration of Christmas was associated in Britain with the countryside and peasant revels, disconnected to the increasing urbanisation and industrialisation taking place.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Davis considers that in *A Christmas Carol*, Dickens showed that Christmas could be celebrated in towns and cities, despite increasing modernisation.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The modern observance of Christmas in English-speaking countries is largely the result of a Victorian-era revival of the holiday.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The Oxford Movement of the 1830s and 1840s had produced a resurgence of the traditional rituals and religious observances associated with Christmastide and, with *A Christmas Carol*, Dickens captured the zeitgeist while he reflected and reinforced his vision of Christmas.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Dickens advocated a humanitarian focus of the holiday, which influenced several aspects of Christmas that are still celebrated in Western culture, such as family gatherings, seasonal food and drink, dancing, games and a festive generosity of spirit.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The historian Ronald Hutton writes that Dickens "linked worship and feasting, within a context of social reconciliation".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The writer James Joyce considered that Dickens took a childish approach with *A Christmas Carol*, producing a gap between the naïve optimism of the story and the realities of life at the time.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Ruth Glancy, the professor of English literature, states that the largest impact of *A Christmas Carol* was the influence felt by individual readers.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In 1867 one American businessman was so moved by attending a reading that he closed his factory on Christmas Day and sent every employee a turkey, while in the early years of the 20th century Maud of Wales—the Queen of Norway—sent gifts to London's crippled children signed "With Tiny Tim's Love".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Chesterton wrote "The beauty and blessing of the story ... lie in the great furnace of real happiness that glows through Scrooge and everything around him. ...
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] Analysing the changes made to adaptations over time, Davis sees changes to the focus of the story and its characters to reflect mainstream thinking of the period.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] While Dickens's Victorian audiences would have viewed the tale as a spiritual but secular parable, in the early 20th century it became a children's story, read by parents who remembered their parents reading it when they were younger.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In the lead-up to and during the Great Depression, Davis suggests that while some saw the story as a "denunciation of capitalism, ...most read it as a way to escape oppressive economic realities".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] The film versions of the 1930s were different in the UK and US.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] British-made films showed a traditional telling of the story, while US-made works showed Cratchit in a more central role, escaping the depression caused by European bankers and celebrating what Davis calls "the Christmas of the common man".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] In the 1960s, Scrooge was sometimes portrayed as a Freudian figure wrestling with his past.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-christmas-carol] By the 1980s he was again set in a world of depression and economic uncertainty.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas**" (often called "**The Night Before Christmas**" and "**'Twas the Night Before Christmas**", from its first line) is a poem, first published anonymously under the title "**Account of a Visit from St.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Authorship has been attributed to Clement Clarke Moore, who claimed authorship in 1837; but it has also been suggested that Henry Livingston Jr. wrote it.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The poem has been called "arguably the best-known verses ever written by an American" and is largely responsible for some of the conceptions of Santa Claus from the mid-19th century to today.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It has had a massive effect on the history of Christmas gift-giving.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Before the poem gained wide popularity, American ideas had varied considerably about Saint Nicholas and other Christmastide visitors.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas" was later set to music and has been recorded by several artists.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] On the night of Christmas Eve, a family is settling down to sleep, when the father is awakened by noises on their lawn.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Looking out the window, he sees Santa Claus, also known as Saint Nicholas, in a sleigh pulled by eight reindeer.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] After landing his sleigh on the roof, Santa bounds down the chimney.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] He carries a sack of toys, and the father watches his visitor deliver presents and fill the stockings hanging by the fireplace, and laughs to himself.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] They share a conspiratorial moment before Santa bounds up the chimney again.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The authorship of *A Visit* is credited to Clement Clarke Moore who is said to have composed it on a snowy winter's day during a shopping trip on a sleigh.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] His inspiration for the character of Saint Nicholas was a local Dutch handyman as well as the historic Saint Nicholas.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore originated many of the features that are still associated with Santa Claus today while borrowing other aspects, such as the use of reindeer.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The poem was first published anonymously in the Troy, New York *Sentinel* on December 23, 1823, having been sent there by a friend of Moore, and was reprinted frequently thereafter with no name attached.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It was first attributed in print to Moore in 1837.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In 1842, the noted poet and editor William Cullen Bryant credited Moore as the author when he included the piece in an anthology of American poetry he had compiled.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore himself acknowledged authorship when he included it in his own book of poems in 1844.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] By then, the original publisher and at least seven others had already acknowledged his authorship.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore had a reputation as an erudite professor and had not wished at first to be connected with the unscholarly verse.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] He included it in the anthology at the insistence of his children, for whom he had originally written the piece.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore's conception of Saint Nicholas was borrowed from his friend Washington Irving, but Moore portrayed his "jolly old elf" as arriving on Christmas Eve rather than Christmas Day.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] At the time that Moore wrote the poem, Christmas Day was overtaking New Year's Day as the preferred genteel family holiday of the season, but some Protestants viewed Christmas as the result of "Catholic ignorance and deception" and still had reservations.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] By having Saint Nicholas arrive the night before, Moore "deftly shifted the focus away from Christmas Day with its still-problematic religious associations".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore's connection with the poem has been questioned by Professor Donald Foster, who used textual content analysis and external evidence to argue that Moore could not have been the author.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Foster believes that Major Henry Livingston Jr., a New Yorker with Dutch and Scottish roots, should be considered the chief candidate for authorship, a view long espoused by the Livingston family.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Livingston was distantly related to Moore's wife.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Foster's claim, however, has been countered by document dealer and historian Seth Kaller, who once owned one of Moore's original manuscripts of the poem.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] On January 20, 1829, Troy editor Orville L.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Holley alluded to the author of the Christmas poem, using terms that accurately described Moore as a native and current resident of New York City, and as "a gentleman of *more* merit as a scholar and a writer than many of more noisy pretensions".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In December 1833, a diary entry by Francis P.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Lee, a student at General Theological Seminary when Moore taught there, referred to a holiday figure of St.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas as being "robed in fur, and dressed according to the description of Prof.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas* appeared under Moore's name in *The New-York Book of Poetry*, edited by Charles Fenno Hoffman (New York: George Dearborn, 1837).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore stated in a letter to the editor of the New York American (published on March 1, 1844) that he "gave the publisher" of *The New-York Book of Poetry* "several pieces, among which was the 'Visit from St.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas.'" Admitting that he wrote it "not for publication, but to amuse my children," Moore claimed the Christmas poem in this 1844 letter as his "literary property, however small the intrinsic value of that property may be".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] 124–27 in Moore's volume of collected *Poems* (New York: Bartlett and Welford, 1844).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Prior to 1844, the poem was included in two 1840 anthologies, attributed to "Clement C.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore" in *Selections from The American Poets*, edited by William Cullen Bryant (New York: Harper & Brothers, 1840), pp.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore" in the first volume of *The Poets of America*, edited by John Keese (New York: S.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The New-York Historical Society has a later manuscript of the poem in Moore's handwriting, forwarded by T.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore along with a cover letter dated March 15, 1862, giving circumstances of the poem's original composition and transmission after a personal "interview" with Clement C.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas" appeared under Moore's name in the 1837 *New-York Book of Poetry*, newspaper printings of the poem often credited Moore as the author.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] For example, the poem is credited to "Professor Moore" in the December 25, 1837 *Pennsylvania Inquirer and Daily Courier*.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Although Moore did not authorize the earliest publication of the poem in the Troy *Sentinel*, he had close ties to Troy through the Protestant Episcopal Church that could explain how it got there.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Harriet Butler of Troy, New York (daughter of the Rev.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] David Butler) who allegedly showed the poem to *Sentinel* editor Orville L.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Holley, was a family friend of Moore's and possibly a distant relative.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] A letter to Moore from the publisher Norman Tuttle states, "I understand from Mr.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Daniel Sackett who was then a merchant in this city".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The reported involvement of two women, Harriet Butler and Sarah Sackett, as intermediaries is consistent with the 1862 account of the poem's earliest transmission in which T.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore describes two stages of copying, first "by a relative of Dr Moores in her Album" and second, "by a friend of hers, from Troy".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore preferred to be known for his more scholarly works, but allowed the poem to be included in his anthology in 1844 at the request of his children.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] By that time, the original publisher and at least seven others had already acknowledged his authorship.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Livingston family lore gives credit to their forebear rather than Moore, but there is no proof that Livingston himself ever claimed authorship, nor has any record ever been found of any printing of the poem with Livingston's name attached to it, despite more than 40 years of searches.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] While textual analyses by English scholars have pointed to Livingston as the likelier author, subsequent tests using forensic linguistics techniques developed by computer scientists have come to the opposite conclusion.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In his 2023 book *The Fight for "The Night": Resolving the Authorship Dispute over "The Night Before Christmas,"* retired litigator Tom A.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Jerman reported using Duquesne University computer scientist Patrick Juola's Java Graphical Authorship Attribution Program to compare the poem to the works of Moore and Livingston, with 16 of 17 tests pointing to Moore as the likelier author.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Advocates for Livingston's authorship argue that Moore "tried at first to disavow" the poem.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] They also posit that Moore falsely claimed to have translated a book.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Document dealer and historian Seth Kaller has challenged both claims.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Kaller examined the book in question, *A Complete Treatise on Merinos and Other Sheep*, as well as many letters signed by Moore, and found that the "signature" was not penned by Moore, and thus provides no evidence that Moore made any plagiaristic claim.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Kaller's findings were confirmed by autograph expert James Lowe, by Dr.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Joe Nickell, the author of *Pen, Ink & Evidence,* and by others.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] According to Kaller, Moore's name was likely written on the book by a New-York Historical Society cataloger to indicate that it had been a gift from Moore to the Society.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Livingston also wrote poetry primarily using an anapaestic metrical scheme, and it is claimed that some of the phraseology of "A Visit" is consistent with other poems by Livingston, and that Livingston's poetry is more optimistic than Moore's poetry published in his own name.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] But Stephen Nissenbaum argues in *Battle for Christmas* that the poem could have been a social satire of the Victorianization of Christmas.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Kaller claims that Foster cherry-picked only the poems that fit his thesis and that many of Moore's unpublished works have a tenor, phraseology, and meter similar to "A Visit".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore had even written a letter titled "From Saint Nicholas" that may have predated 1823.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Foster also contends that Moore hated tobacco and would, therefore, never have depicted Saint Nicholas with a pipe.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] However, Kaller notes, the source of evidence for Moore's supposed disapproval of tobacco is *The Wine Drinker*, another poem by him.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In actuality, that verse contradicts such a claim.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore's *The Wine Drinker* criticizes self-righteous, hypocritical advocates of temperance who secretly indulge in the substances which they publicly oppose, and supports the social use of tobacco in moderation and wine and opium, which was more acceptable then than now.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Foster also asserts that Livingston's mother was Dutch, which accounts for the references to the Dutch *Sinteklaes* tradition and the use of the Dutch names "Dunder and Blixem".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Against this claim, it is suggested by Kaller that Moore – a friend of writer Washington Irving and member of the same literary society – may have acquired some of his knowledge of New York Dutch traditions from Irving.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Irving had written *A History of New York* in 1809 under the name of "Dietrich Knickerbocker".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Jackson, a professor emeritus at the University of Auckland and a fellow at the Royal Society of New Zealand, authored a book in 2016, *Who Wrote "The Night Before Christmas"?: Analyzing the Clement Clarke Moore Vs.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Henry Livingston Question*, in which he evaluates the opposing arguments, using author-attribution techniques of modern computational stylistics to examine the long-standing controversy.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Employing a range of tests, including a statistical analysis of phonemes, Jackson contends that Livingston authored the classic poem.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The latter 1963 stereo recording for Capitol Records became the most familiar of the poem's musical adaptations.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Christmas song-writing specialist Johnny Marks also composed a short version in 1952, titled "The Night Before Christmas Song", which has been recorded multiple times.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It was also arranged for choir by Lee Kjelson and Margaret Shelley Vance.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The poem was also set to music by British child composer Alma Deutscher (b.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In 1953, Perry Como recorded a recitation of the poem for RCA Victor with background music arranged and conducted by Mitchell Ayres.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Louis Armstrong recited the poem in a March 1971 recording made only four months before his death.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It was recorded at his home in Corona, Queens and released as 45 rpm by Continental Records.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Jo Stafford recorded a version of "'Twas The Night Before Christmas" as part of her 1955 album *Happy Holiday*.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The first completely musical rendition, that used the text of the poem in its entirety without material additions or alterations, was the cantata "A Visit from St.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Dressel in 1992 and first performed by the Webster University Orchestra, SATB Soloists, and Chorus.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] More recent performances of the cantata have been performed by regional orchestras and choruses in Missouri, Illinois and Colorado.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Four hand-written copies of the poem are known to exist and three are in museums, including the New-York Historical Society library.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The fourth copy, written out and signed by Clement Clarke Moore as a gift to a friend in 1860, was sold by one private collector to another in December 2006.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It was purchased for $280,000 by an unnamed "chief executive officer of a media company" who resides in New York City, according to Heritage Auctions which brokered the private sale.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The poem is read or recited in numerous Christmas films, including *Prancer* (1989), *National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation* (1989), *The Santa Clause* (1994), *Reindeer Games* (2000), and *Falling for Christmas* (2016).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It also inspired two television specials called *'Twas the Night Before Christmas*, made in 1974 and 1977.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] '*Twas the Night Before Christmas* (2022) is a Hallmark Channel film about a town's annual Christmas Eve courtroom production debating the true authorship of the poem.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] It is related in the Bible by Matthew 2:11: "On entering the house, they saw the child with Mary his mother; and they knelt down and paid him homage.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Then, opening their treasure chests, they offered him gifts of gold, frankincense, and myrrh.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] And having been warned in a dream not to return to Herod, they left for their own country by another path".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Christian iconography considerably expanded the bare account of the Biblical Magi described in the Gospel of Matthew (2:1–22).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] By the later Middle Ages this drew from non-canonical sources like the Golden Legend by Jacobus de Voragine.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Artists used the expanded Christian iconography to reinforce the idea that Jesus was recognized, from his earliest infancy, as king of the earth.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The adoration scene was often used to represent the Nativity, one of the most indispensable episodes in cycles of the *Life of the Virgin* as well as the *Life of Christ*.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Stories throughout the Middle Ages started circulating, which speculated who exactly were the three kings who were famous for visiting the Christ child.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Many people assumed that they came from somewhere in the east.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Eventually it was decided that the three kings would represent the three main continents at the time; Europe, Asia, and Africa.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The three names that prevailed over the centuries for the three kings were Gaspar (or Caspar), Melchior, and Balthasar.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The prominence of this story, as well as the three kings or magi, is due to the great theological significance that the Biblical story holds, their exotic clothes and looks, as well as their great and expensive gifts.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] In the church calendar, the event is commemorated in Western Christianity as the Feast of the Epiphany (January 6).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The Eastern Orthodox Church commemorates the Adoration of the Magi on the Feast of the Nativity (December 25).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The term is anglicized from the Vulgate Latin section title for this passage: **A Magis adoratur**.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] In the earliest depictions, the Magi are shown wearing Persian dress of trousers and Phrygian caps, usually in profile, advancing in step with their gifts held out before them.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] These images adapt Late Antique poses for barbarians submitting to an Emperor, and presenting golden wreaths, and indeed relate to images of tribute-bearers from various Mediterranean and ancient Near Eastern cultures going back many centuries.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The earliest are from catacomb paintings and sarcophagus reliefs of the 4th century.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Crowns are first seen in the 10th century, mostly in the West, where their dress had by that time lost any Oriental flavour in most cases.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The standard Byzantine depiction of the Nativity included the journey or arrival of the mounted Magi in the background, but not them presenting their gifts, until the post-Byzantine period, when the western depiction was often adapted to an icon style.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Later Byzantine images often show small pill-box like hats, whose significance is disputed.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The Magi are usually shown as the same age until about this period, but then the idea of depicting the three ages of man is introduced: a particularly beautiful example is seen on the façade of the cathedral of Orvieto.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Occasionally from the 12th century, and very often in Northern Europe from the 15th, the Magi are also made to represent the three known parts of the world: Balthasar is very commonly cast as a young African or Moor, and old Caspar is given Oriental features or, more often, dress.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Melchior represents Europe and middle age.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Early Renaissance paintings of this theme, such as by Fra Angelico and Fra Lippi, emphasize the pomp and pageantry of the scene.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] From the 14th century onward, large retinues are often shown, the gifts are contained in spectacular pieces of goldsmith work, and the Magi's clothes are given increasing attention.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The subject was especially popular with the artists of Antwerp Mannerism from about 1500 to 1530.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] These mostly anonymous artists lived in the Golden Age of Antwerp, as it took over from Bruges as the leading business city of the Low Countries, capturing a huge proportion of the explosion in international trade that followed the development by the Portuguese of the sea route from Asia.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The Magis were regarded as the patron saints of travelling merchants, and so international trade in general, and large numbers of their patrons no doubt came from the various international business communities from different countries resident in Antwerp.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] In the Greek world, Cretan painter Michael Damaskinos revitalized the Greek Italian Byzantine style by mixing it with Venetian painting in his rendition of the *Adoration of the Magi* around 1590.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The island of Crete was held by the Venetian Empire, and the painting style was known as the Cretan School.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The scene often includes a fair diversity of animals as well: the ox and ass from the Nativity scene are usually there, but also the horses, camels, dogs, and falcons of the kings and their retinue, and sometimes other animals, such as birds in the rafters of the stable.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Other subjects include the Journey of the Magi, where they and perhaps their retinue are the only figures, usually shown following the Star of Bethlehem, and there are relatively uncommon scenes of their meeting with Herod and the *Dream of the Magi*.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The usefulness of the subject to the Church and the technical challenges involved in representing it have made the Adoration of the Magi a favorite subject of Christian art: chiefly painting, but also sculpture and even music (as in Gian-Carlo Menotti's opera *Amahl and the Night Visitors*).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The subject matter is also found in stained glass.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] The first figural stained glass window made in the United States is the "Adoration of the Magi" window located at Christ Church, Pelham, New York and designed in 1843 by the founder and first rector's son, William Jay Bolton.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] Many hundreds of artists have treated the subject.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/adoration-of-the-magi] A partial list of those with articles follows.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] Prior to the Reformation of 1560, Christmas in Scotland, then called "Yule" (alternative spellings include Yhoill, Yuil, Ȝule and Ȝoull; see Yogh) or in Gaelic-speaking areas "Nollaig", was celebrated in a similar fashion to the rest of Catholic Europe.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] Calderwood recorded that in 1545, a few months before his murder, Cardinal Beaton had "passed over the Christmasse dayes with games and feasting".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] A 1640 act of the Parliament of Scotland abolished the "Yule vacation and all observation thereof in time coming".
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] Two acts of the Estates of Parliament — the **Yule Vacance Act 1640** (*Act discharging the Yule vacance*) (5 June 1640) and the **Yule Vacance Act 1690** (April c.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] 52) *Act dischargeing the Yule vacance* (15 April 1690)— abolished the Yule Vacance (Christmas recess).
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] The first act was partly repealed by the **Yule Vacance Act 1686** (c.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] 7), when Episcopalianism was briefly in ascendancy within the Kirk.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] The second act was partly repealed in 1712 by the **Yule Vacance Act 1711** (10 Ann. c.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] The third act was repealed by the **Yule Vacance Act 1714** (1 Geo.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] The period of festivities running from Christmas to Handsel Monday, including Hogmanay and Ne'erday, is known as the Daft Days.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] Christmas in Scotland was traditionally observed very quietly because of the various Acts (listed above) that had suppressed Christmas celebrations in Scotland after the Reformation.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] Christmas Day was made a public holiday in 1958 in Scotland, Boxing Day only in 1974.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] The New Year's Eve festivity, Hogmanay, was by far the largest celebration in Scotland.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] The giftgiving, public holidays and feasting associated with mid-winter were traditionally held between 11 December and 6 January.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] However, since the 1980s, the fading of the Church's influence and the increased influences from the rest of the United Kingdom and elsewhere, Christmas and its related festivities are now nearly on par with, or surpass, Hogmanay and Ne'erday.
[src:christmas-in-scotland/christmas-in-scotland] Edinburgh, Glasgow and other cities now have traditional German Christmas markets from late November until Christmas Eve.
